\subsection{Loss-bias check on dropped CRunDec draws}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

Approximately $33\%$ of random-spectrum Model~A draws fail to produce valid CRunDec output for running claims (specifically $3{,}269$ of $10{,}000$ in the baseline run); failures occur when the random spectrum produces pathological QCD configurations (charm-bottom thresholds too close, $\alpha_s$ blow-up, etc.). To check whether this loss biases the reported $p$-values, we performed two diagnostics.

\paragraph{Distributional comparison of dropped vs.\ retained draws.} Using the surrogate running scheme, we compared the distribution of best residuals for the dropped draws against the same distribution for the successful draws. The two distributions differ: dropped draws have a median best residual of $8.05 \times 10^{-5}$ versus $5.66 \times 10^{-5}$ for successful draws (ratio $1.42$); a two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test gives $p_{\text{KS}} \approx 8.5 \times 10^{-26}$. These observations are suggestive of stochastic dominance of the dropped-draw best-residual distribution over the retained-draw distribution, which would imply that excluding the dropped draws biases reported tail probabilities upward (i.e., conservatively). Two caveats prevent us from treating this as a validated conservativeness claim: the comparison routes through the surrogate running scheme that did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), and median/KS evidence does not prove stochastic dominance at the full distributional level.

\paragraph{Engine-switching crosscheck.} As a second diagnostic, we re-ran Model~A using 2-loop CRunDec in place of 4-loop, on paired random-spectrum draws ($N = 10{,}000$). The failure set is identical: the same $3{,}269$ draws fail at both loop orders, and the retained sets coincide. The failures are therefore intrinsic to the pathological mass spectra rather than to loop-order specifics, and alternative RG solvers do not reduce the dropout rate or give access to the dropped-draw full-pipeline values. Engine-switching does not provide a way to quantify the dropout bias directly.

\paragraph{Summary.} We do not claim that the reported Model~A tail probabilities are upper bounds on the true tail probabilities. We report them as values computed on the subset of draws for which full CRunDec succeeds, note the direction-of-bias conjecture above as supported by suggestive but not conclusive evidence, and flag that the induced bias on the reported tail probabilities cannot be determined without the unavailable full-pipeline values for the dropped draws. The qualitative ranking of claims is unaffected by this exclusion since it acts uniformly across claims. The engine-switching exercise did, however, reveal a separate loop-order systematic on the absolute Model~A tail probabilities (see Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}).

\subsection{Loop-order dependence of absolute Model~A tail probabilities}
\label{sec:loop-order}

The 2-loop crosscheck run in Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias} yielded a full-search Model~A tail probability of $0.037 \pm 0.002$ on the retained subset, compared with $0.5027 \pm 0.0019$ at 4-loop on the identical retained subset. The two numbers refer to the same audited search under the same dropout exclusion, differing only in the perturbative order of the running implementation. The factor of $\approx 13$ difference is a direct measurement of the sensitivity of the Model~A null distribution to RG truncation order: higher-order running produces more ``knobs'' through threshold matching and running-coefficient structure, which changes the shape of the null distribution of best residuals across the search space.

This is not a quantitative statement about physical truncation uncertainty in the individual $Q$ values (4-loop is the physically correct order we use throughout, and individual $Q(\mu_i)$ values are stable to well below the $\sigma_Q$ floor). It is a statement about the Monte Carlo null itself: the absolute Model~A tail probabilities carry a loop-order systematic at the factor-of-$\sim 10$ level. This is an additional reason---on top of the prior-class dependence of Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}---to read Model~A tail probabilities as within-configuration relative rankings rather than as absolute significance levels. All Model~A numbers reported in the main text and Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} use 4-loop running on every draw.



