\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{What the analysis says about Koide-type quark relations}

Three observations follow.

First, no claim involving search across multiple triples combined with running has a low tail probability under either null model. The full-search $p \approx 0.5$ is not a marginal failure; it is fully consistent with noise under both audited tools, and the conclusion is stable across hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A, the four correlation choices for Model~B, and three alternative priors. The $\approx 33\%$ CRunDec dropout in Model~A introduces an unverified direction-of-bias on reported tail probabilities (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}); this affects absolute values but acts uniformly across claims, so the qualitative ranking is preserved.

Second, single-triple claims proposed in prior literature occupy a different position from the full search. The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ has $p = 0.0025 \pm 0.0002$ under Model~A within the chosen log-uniform prior class (binomial SE at $N = 100{,}000$); under hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A it has $p = 0.004$--$0.007$ (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}). Its Model~B tail probability is $\approx 0.15$, which restates that its observed residual is $\approx 0.09\sigma_Q$ and carries no independent evidential content beyond that ratio. With $N = 100{,}000$ the MC uncertainty on the small Model~A values is well controlled (SE of order $10^{-4}$, Table~\ref{tab:pvalues}); the dominant remaining uncertainties on these absolute numbers are the prior-class dependence (Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}) and the loop-order dependence (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}).

One feature of this particular claim warrants explicit statement rather than inference from the reference list. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ hypothesis was published by the present author~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, and the analysis reported here began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space so that the same criteria could be applied uniformly to proposals by Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011}, Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011}, and Cao~\citep{Cao2012}. The claim is therefore pre-specified relative to the present audit, but it is not pre-registered against future data: it was formulated on the same FLAG/PDG central values the audit uses, and the prior publication is by the present author rather than by a third party. The reported $p = 0.002$ is a multiplicity-corrected characterization of that prior claim under the present audited search space and the chosen log-uniform prior; it is not an independent confirmation. The temporal-trajectory test introduced in Section~\ref{sec:temporal} is what a forward-looking assessment of this particular claim would draw on.

Third, Table~\ref{tab:phase1} and the matched-complexity knob-isolation test of Section~\ref{sec:isolation} together indicate that admitting non-self-scale running shifts the Model~A null distribution of best residuals toward smaller values by more than trial-count multiplicity alone accounts for (Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}). At matched subsample size $N' = 80$, running-only draws yield a median tail probability of $0.61$ while signs-only yields $0.38$, indicating that non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the noise floor of this search and not merely a vehicle for more trials. The observed closure at full freedom is typical under the full-freedom null ($p \approx 0.50$); this does not establish that non-self-scale running is illegitimate as a physical operation, only that searches admitting it need to be compared against null distributions that also admit it.

\subsection{Falsifiability of the surviving single-triple claim}

A statistical test against null models speaks to present-day significance. A separate question is whether a claim with a low tail probability under one null model is stable to anticipated improvements in mass measurements.

The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ has residual $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$, currently $0.09\sigma_Q$. The dominant uncertainty contribution is $m_t$ ($\sim 86\%$ of variance). Even at projected FCC-ee precision ($\sigma_{m_t} \approx 0.05$~GeV, a $14\times$ improvement), the residual-to-uncertainty ratio reaches only $\sim 0.2\sigma$, so the closure is unlikely to become testable for exactness within foreseeable experimental precision. It would be falsified if the $m_t$ central value drifts by more than $\sim 0.5$~GeV ($0.7\sigma$ of current uncertainty), or if $m_c(m_c)$ or $m_b(m_b)$ shift by comparable fractions of their uncertainties.

